<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-462-191  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 462 191.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  August 27 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Thackeray and EFF co-founder criticize &quot;hacker challenge.&quot;andO;(Arizona assistant attorney general Gail Thackeray and ElectronicFrontier Foundation's John Perry Barlow)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   LeeMah Datacom Security Corp. (competitions).andO;Topic:     Computer hackersContestsPublic RelationsLegal Issues.andO;Person:    Barlow, John Perry (attitudes); Thackeray, Gail (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>THACKERAY AND EFF CO-FOUNDER CRITICIZE &quot;HACKER CHALLENGE&quot; NEW YORK, NEW YORK,U.S.A., 1990 AUG 27 (NB) -- Gail Thackeray, assistant Arizona attorneygeneral and John Perry Barlow, co-founder of the Electronic FrontierFoundation (EFF), in interviews with Newsbytes, both strongly criticized thepromotion announced by LeeMah DataCom Security Security Corp. whichchallenges &quot;hackers&quot; to attempt to break into their security system.andM;The company has stored a secret message in personal computers located in theNew York and San Francisco offices of the accounting firm Coppers andamp; Lybrandwhich is overseeing the contest.andP;  The first person to gain access to themessage will win a vacation for two to Tahiti or San Moritz, Switzerland.andO;LeeMah DataCom provides security systems and the contest, according to LeeMahPresident John Tuomy, is to show that computer systems can be secured, &quot;Wewant to show the world that hackers can be beaten.&quot;andM;Thackeray told Newsbytes: &quot;It's irresponsible and gives hackers somejustification for their claim that what they are doing is good for society.&quot;andO;Barlow commented: &quot;And, for the 1994 Olympics, medals in safe-cracking andembezzlement.andP;  It is clearly in the commercial interest of DataCom tomythologize crackers, but I don't believe that the public is well served bythis sort of thing.&quot;andM;Other criticism was voiced by Ian Murphy, a Philadelphia security expert andself-described hacker know as Captain Zap.andP;  Murphy was quoted as saying: &quot;Oneproblem you have with this contest is they are advocating tele-crime.andO;Hackers don't pay phone bills.&quot; Murphy's comments relate to frequent chargesthat hackers avoid paying telephone charges by using credit card numbersfound on bulletin boards.andM;Tuomy was quoted as saying that he did not hear any reports of credit cardabuse relating to last year's contest and that he assumed that LeeMah wouldhave been notified by the telephone company had such things occurred.andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19900827)</TEXT></DOC>